  "body": "{\"query\":\"WCAG 2.2 quick reference accessibility official contrast keyboard responsive\",\"follow_up_questions\":null,\"answer\":null,\"images\":[],\"results\":[{\"url\":\"https://www.getstark.co/blog/wcag-2-2\",\"title\":\"Understanding the new WCAG 2.2 criteria\",\"content\":\"## Understanding the new WCAG 2.2 criteria. Breaking down the 9 new WCAG 2.2 criteria, what they mean for your team and your products, and how you can seamlessly integrate them into your process. Overview of the latest changes to 2.2. In October, the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.2 became the official recommendation of the W3C. We want to make sure you have all of the information you need to ensure your products are accessible. WCAG 2.2 emphasizes keyboard navigability, enhancing user focus. The guidelines specify that focus indicators, when visible, should be sufficiently large and contrasted, with an area at least as large as a 2 pixel thick perimeter of the unfocused component and a contrast ratio of at least 3:1. **Visibility of Essential Controls (3.2.7)**. As we embrace the guidelines within WCAG 2.2, it's important to understand them so we can make actionable moves towards implementing them — and in turn creating a more inclusive world.\",\"score\":0.6757865,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.deque.com/blog/wcag-2-2-is-at-the-proposed-recommendation-stage\",\"title\":\"WCAG 2.2: Proposed Recommendation - Deque\",\"content\":\"A new version of the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) is almost ready. If you are already familiar with WCAG 2.0 and/or 2.1, you probably have a number of questions. The Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) have been the standard for digital accessibility the world around for over two decades. Before the end of August 2023, the W3C hopes to publish version 2.2 of WCAG. WCAG 2.2 will add several new success criteria focused on extending requirements for users with low vision, cognitive impairments, and limited fine motor skills. These two success criteria will help sighted users who depend on a keyboard to navigate a web page by making sure the component and its focus indicator aren’t overlapped by other content. This AAA success criterion will require a clearly visible “focus indicator” that shows the current point of focus of the keyboard. This goes beyond the existing 2.4.7 Focus Visible requirement in that it defines a minimum size of the focus indicator and a minimum contrast of 3:1.\",\"score\":0.6554468,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.audioeye.com/post/wcag-22-quick-reference-guide\",\"title\":\"WCAG 2.2 Quick Reference: 11 Easy Ways to Test Accessibility\",\"content\":\"Check your site’s accessibility for free. # WCAG 2.2: 11 Easy Ways to Test Accessibility. WCAG 2.2 introduced nine new success criteria to enhance accessibility for users with disabilities, particularly on mobile devices. Below, you’ll learn how WCAG 2.2 differs from WCAG 2.1 and quick ways to test your digital for 2.2 conformance — no deep technical knowledge required. Keep Accessibility Simple — and Scalable — with AudioEye. Enter URL to find accessibility issues on your site. Enter the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.2 — the latest version of WCAG guidelines. While it hasn’t officially replaced WCAG 2.1 Level AA as the legal benchmark for compliance, adopting the new success criteria now can help you stay ahead of lawsuits and make your content work for more users. 2.2 and fast, simple ways to test your content for conformance with the latest version — no deep technical expertise required. With a better understanding of WCAG 2.2 in mind, let’s look at how to check your digital content against WCAG 2.2.\",\"score\":0.6002124,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG22\",\"title\":\"Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.2 - W3C\",\"content\":\"# Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.2. Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.2 covers a wide range of recommendations for making web content more accessible. Following these guidelines will make content more accessible to a wider range of people with disabilities, including accommodations for blindness and low vision, deafness and hearing loss, limited movement, speech disabilities, photosensitivity, and combinations of these, and some accommodation for learning disabilities and cognitive limitations; but will not address every user need for people with these disabilities. WCAG 2.2 extends Web Content Accessibility Guidelines 2.1 [WCAG21 2.1\\\")], which was published as a W3C Recommendation June 2018. Content that conforms to WCAG 2.2 also conforms to WCAG 2.0 and WCAG 2.1. The WG intends that for policies requiring conformance to WCAG 2.0 or WCAG 2.1, WCAG 2.2 can provide an alternate means of conformance. The publication of WCAG 2.2 does not deprecate or supersede WCAG 2.0 or WCAG 2.1. While WCAG 2.0 and WCAG 2.1 remain W3C Recommendations, the W3C advises the use of WCAG 2.2 to maximize future applicability of accessibility efforts.\",\"score\":0.50856906,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://guia-wcag.com/en\",\"title\":\"WCAG - Quick reference guide\",\"content\":\"WCAG Guide Logo - the word guide in a handwritten font and the letters WCAG in a capitalized font. # WCAG 2.2 easy! In a sentence, it is: **\\\"the fundamental basis for you to have truly inclusive and accessible digital products\\\"**. These cards are not a substitute for reading the full criteria, it's just a simpler way of trying to understand them. * ### 1.1.1 Non-text Content [A]. Any content \\\"non-textual\\\" and relevant to understanding the information, must bring an alternative text description (visible or not) to identify the content (e.g., including captcha). * ### 1.2.1 Audio-only and Video-only (Prerecorded) [A]. * ### 1.2.2 Captions (Prerecorded) [A]. * ### 1.2.3 Audio Description or Media Alternative (Prerecorded) [A]. An audio description or a descriptive text transcript must be provided for all prerecorded video content. **Note:** if an audio description is provided, criterion 1.2.5 (AA) will be met. If a transcript is provided, criterion 1.2.8 (AAA) will be met. * ### 1.2.5 Audio Description (Prerecorded) [AA].\",\"score\":0.48177138,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@michaelmoubani/wcag-2-2-accessibility-guide-34927b655913\",\"title\":\"WCAG 2.2 Accessibility Guide - Medium\",\"content\":\"2.4 Navigable. Highlight links or buttons when they're selected. This helps keyboard-only users know where they are on the page. SC 2.4.\",\"score\":0.4757764,\"raw_content\":null}],\"response_time\":0.65,\"request_id\":\"01e7afca-1e3b-471c-ac83-4434e797388a\"}"
